<title>New refund policies from Alibaba’s Taobao and JD.com spark fears of customer abuse among merchants</title>
<link>https://www.scmp.com/tech/big-tech/article/3247168/new-refund-policies-alibabas-taobao-and-jdcom-spark-fears-customer-abuse-among-merchants</link>
<description><![CDATA[ <div>  <h2>Summary：</h2>  Chinese e-commerce platforms such as Taobao and JD.com have introduced new "refund only" policies, allowing consumers to receive a refund for a product they are unhappy with even if they keep it. While this aim at protecting consumer rights, it has raised concerns among some merchants about potential abuse of the policy and its impact on their operations.  <ul>    <li>Main information: Introduction of "refund only" policies by Taobao and JD.com; circumstances in which consumers can receive a refund; concerns of merchants regarding abuse and increased claims; possible impact on sellers who invest in high-quality products.</li>    <li>Theme: The potential pros and cons of the new refund policies on Chinese e-commerce platforms, including benefits for consumers and challenges for merchants.</li>    <li>Viewpoint: The need to balance consumer rights with the interests of merchants; the importance of establishing clear guidelines and criteria to prevent abuse of the refund policies.</li>  </ul></div><div>  <h2>总结：</h2>  中国淘宝、京东等电商平台推出了新的“先退款，再退货”政策，允许消费者在对产品不满意的情况下，即使不退回产品也可以退款。虽然此举旨在保护消费者权益，但也引发了部分商家对于政策被滥用以及对自身运营产生影响的担忧。  <ul>    <li>主要信息：淘宝、京东推出“先退款，再退货”政策；消费者可以退款的情况；商家对政策被滥用以及索赔增多表示担忧；对销售高质量产品的商家可能产生的影响。</li>    <li>主题：中国电商平台新退款政策的潜在利弊，包括对消费者的好处和对商家的挑战。</li>    <li>观点：需要在消费者权益和商家利益之间取得平衡；必须建立清晰的准则和标准，以防止退款政策被滥用。</li>  </ul></div><div>  <h2>单词：</h2>  <ul>    <li>exploit (v.) - /ɪkˈsplɔɪt/ 利用，剥削。    <p>原文例句：Some merchants have raised concerns that consumers may look to exploit the terms of these ‘refund only’ policies, hitting their operations. </p>    <p>例句讲解：这个单词来源于拉丁语，由ex-（出来）和plere（填充）组成，表示“利用，剥削”。在这个例句中，它指的是一些消费者可能试图利用这些“仅退款”政策的条款，损害其运营。</p></li>  </ul>  <ul>    <li>abuse (n.) - /əˈbjuːs/ 滥用，误用。    <p>原文例句：One user with the handle “PengqiangweiVerna” posted on Weibo that the practice will “foster a group of online freeloaders”. </p>    <p>例句讲解：这个单词来源于拉丁语，由ab-（远离）和usus（使用）组成，表示“滥用，误用”。在这个例句中，它指的是微博用户“彭强威Verna”认为这种做法将“培养一群网络占便宜的人”。</p></li>  </ul>  </div><div>  <h2>词组：</h2>  <ul>    <li>rock-bottom prices - 极低的价格，最低价格。    <P>原文例句：Pinduoduo’s focus on rock-bottom prices means that the costs of the scheme are more bearable than for merchants on rival sites.</p>    <p>例句讲解：这个词组是由rock-bottom（最低限度）和prices（价格）组成的，表示“极低的价格，最低价格”。在这个例句中，它表示拼多多的主要价格是最低价格，这意味着该计划的成本对于竞争网站上的商家来说更可以承受。</p></li>  </ul></div><div>  <h2>句子：</h2>  <ul>    <li>Pinduoduo’s original “refund but keep the product” practice was initially launched in 2021 and is seen as a key factor behind the Shanghai-based budget-shopping platform’s rise to prominence. - 拼多多的“先退款，再退货”政策首次推出于2021年，被视为这家总部位于上海的预算购物平台崛起的关键因素。<p>句子分析：这是一个复杂句，主句是Pinduoduo’s original “refund but keep the product” practice was initially launched in 2021，其中主语是Pinduoduo’s original “refund but keep the product” practice，谓语是was launched，宾语是in 2021。is seen as a key factor behind the Shanghai-based budget-shopping platform’s rise to prominence是一个现在分词短语作状语，修饰主句，表示拼多多的“先退款，再退货”政策被视为这家总部位于上海的预算购物平台崛起的关键因素。这个句子的意思是说，拼多多的“先退款，再退货”政策首次推出于2021年，被视为这家总部位于上海的预算购物平台崛起的关键因素。</p></li>  </ul></div><div>  <h2>语法：</h2>  <ul>    <li>虚拟语气 - 用于表达说话人对某事的态度或看法,而不陈述事实。    <p>原文例句：The 33-year-old online shop owner, who spoke on condition of anonymity for fear of retribution from the platforms, said that the new refund policy could backfire and hit sellers who invest in high-quality products. </p>    <p>语法讲解：这是一个虚拟语气的用法，表示这位网店店主对新退款政策的看法。主句是said that the new refund policy could backfire and hit sellers who invest in high-quality products，其中said是谓语，that the new refund policy could backfire and hit sellers who invest in high-quality products是一个宾语从句，其中could backfire和hit sellers who invest in high-quality products都是虚拟语气，表示这位网店店主认为新退款政策可能会适得其反，打击那些投资高品质产品的卖家。</p></li>  </ul>   <ul>    <li>过去完成时 - 表示在过去某个时间点之前已经完成的动作或状态。    <p>原文例句：Alibaba, whose company mission is “to make it easy to do business anywhere”, had a long internal debate over whether to follow rival Pinduoduo, which was the first to offer a policy whereby a shopper can receive a refund for a product they are unhappy with even though they do not return it. </p>    <p>语法讲解：这是一个过去完成时的用法，表示阿里巴巴在过去某个时间点之前已经完成了内部辩论。主句是Alibaba had a long internal debate，其中had是谓语，a long internal debate是宾语。over whether to follow rival Pinduoduo是一个介词短语作状语，修饰主句，表示阿里巴巴是否要效仿竞争对手拼多多。which was the first to offer a policy whereby a shopper can receive a refund for a product they are unhappy with even though they do not return it是一个非限制性定语从句，修饰先行词Pinduoduo。在这个从句中，was是谓语，the first to offer a policy whereby a shopper can receive a refund for a product they are unhappy with even though they do not return it是一个宾语从句，其中offer是谓语，a policy whereby a shopper can receive a refund for a product they are unhappy with even though they do not return it是一个宾语从句。这个句子的意思是说，阿里巴巴在过去某个时间点之前已经完成了内部辩论，内容是是否要效仿竞争对手拼多多，因为拼多多是第一家提供消费者可以不退还产品就获得退款的政策的公司。</p></li>  </ul></div>  <ul><li>Taobao and JD.com have introduced policies that allow shoppers to receive a refund for a product they are unhappy with even though they keep it</li>
<li>Some merchants have raised concerns that consumers may look to exploit the terms of these ‘refund only’ policies, hitting their operations</li>
</ul><figure><img src="https://cdn.i-scmp.com/sites/default/files/d8/images/canvas/2024/01/03/85b29bec-f2e3-42ad-ba41-d20ec559a707_664d3160.jpg" /><figcaption>Some merchants have raised concerns about potential abuse under new refund policies. Photo: SCMP</figcaption></figure><p>New “refund only” policies introduced by Chinese e-commerce players including Alibaba Group Holding’s Taobao and JD.com have sparked concern among some sellers about potential abuse of the terms, according to merchants and analysts.</p><p>Taobao and JD.com in late December introduced new policies that – in certain circumstances – allow shoppers to receive a refund for a product they are unhappy with even though they keep it. This may occur when a consumer complains about the poor quality of a product, or about an inaccurate and misleading description on the platform. Alibaba owns the South China Morning Post.</p><p>Alibaba, whose company mission is “to make it easy to do business anywhere”, had a long internal debate over whether to follow rival Pinduoduo, which was the first to offer a policy whereby a shopper can receive a refund for a product they are unhappy with even though they do not return it.</p><p>Even though some merchants have raised concerns about potential abuse, Alibaba came down on the side of consumer rights in such a situation as merchants are ultimately dependent on buyer confidence, according to a person briefed on the discussions who asked not to be identified.</p><h3><a href="https://www.scmp.com/tech/big-tech/article/3246559/chinese-e-commerce-firms-jdcom-and-alibabas-taobao-roll-out-refund-only-policy-shoppers-heating" title="">JD.com, Alibaba’s Taobao push ‘refund only’ policy to rival Pinduoduo’s strategy</a></h3><p>However, since the policy went into effect last week there has been an increased number of claims under the “refund but keep the purchase” policy, according to one merchant who runs apparel shops on both Taobao and JD.com, adding that some consumers were looking to exploit the situation.</p><p>The 33-year-old online shop owner, who spoke on condition of anonymity for fear of retribution from the platforms, said that the new refund policy could backfire and hit sellers who invest in high-quality products, because they will bear higher costs in the event of more claims.</p><p>“This refund terms only works for merchants who sell dirt-cheap goods,” she said, adding that the policy clearly favoured consumers.</p><p>Meanwhile, some merchants took to social media platforms such as Douyin and Weibo to express anger at the potential for policy abuse.</p><p>One user with the handle “PengqiangweiVerna” posted on Weibo that the practice will “foster a group of online freeloaders”. Another Douyin user called “Xinzhouxiaohuolang” posted a dozen videos denouncing such refund requests.</p><p>Both Taobao and JD.com have said that any decisions on refund requests on their platforms will be based on multiple indicators, including the track records of both merchants and buyers, along with big data analysis to support their judgments.</p><p>A person familiar with the situation at Taobao, who asked not to be identified as they are not authorised to talk to the media, said that the platform has offered merchants an appeal option if they think they have been wronged.</p><p>Taobao and JD.com did not immediately respond to requests for comment on Wednesday.</p><p>Pinduoduo’s original “refund but keep the product” practice was initially launched in 2021 and is seen as a key factor behind the Shanghai-based budget-shopping platform’s rise to prominence.</p><p>Tang Guangyao, a 38-year-old Beijing software developer, said he has shifted from other e-commerce platforms to Pinduoduo as a primary shopping channel owing to its robust consumer protection, even though it focuses on budget prices.</p><p>But some analysts say simply following Pinduoduo’s lead may not work for rival platforms.</p><p>“This [new refund policy] isn’t very practical for platforms such as Taobao, Tmall and JD.com,” said Zhang Yi, founder and chief analyst at Guangzhou-based iiMedia, pointing out that Pinduoduo’s focus on rock-bottom prices means that the costs of the scheme are more bearable than for merchants on rival sites.</p><p>“By following this [Pinduoduo] refund policy … [rival platforms] will give their merchants a dilemma,” he added.</p> ]]></description>
