<title>China’s erratic regulatory moves against Big Tech firms must end, says communist party newspaper after video gaming stock rout</title>
<link>https://www.scmp.com/tech/policy/article/3247123/chinas-erratic-regulatory-moves-against-big-tech-firms-must-end-says-communist-party-newspaper-after</link>
<description><![CDATA[ <div>  <h2>Summary：</h2>  The mouthpiece of the Central Party School has urged regulators to stop swaying between lax oversight and overly strict regulation of China’s Big Tech companies, arguing that such erratic moves harm the health of the country’s internet industry.    <ul>    <li>Abstract: The Study Times' opinion piece calls for more stable regulation of China's platform economy to facilitate the growth of domestic internet giants.</li>    <li>Theme: The piece emphasizes the need for balanced regulation to avoid hindering the development and competitiveness of Chinese internet companies.</li>    <li>Viewpoint: The article argues that excessive regulation is detrimental to the platform economy and urges regulators to adopt a more measured approach.</li>    <li>Main information: The piece cites examples of regulatory hostility towards internet firms, such as the NPPA's draft regulation restricting spending on video games, which resulted in significant losses for Chinese gaming stocks.</li>  </ul></div><div>  <h2>总结：</h2>  中央党校机关报发文呼吁监管机构停止对平台经济忽松忽严的监管行为，认为这样会损害国内互联网产业的健康发展。  <ul>    <li>摘要：《学习时报》评论文章呼吁对中国平台经济实施更加稳定的监管，以便国内互联网巨头能够发展壮大。</li>    <li>主题：文章强调平衡监管的必要性，避免妨碍中国互联网企业的发展与竞争力。</li>    <li>观点：文章认为，过度监管不利于平台经济的发展，并呼吁监管机构采取更加有分寸的手段。</li>    <li>主要信息：文章引用了针对互联网企业的监管敌对行为的例子，例如国家新闻出版署发布的限制电子游戏支出的监管草案，导致中国游戏股遭受重大损失。</li>  </ul></div><div>  <h2>单词：</h2>  <ul>    <li>articulate (v.) - /ɑːrtɪkjʊleɪt/ 清楚地表达。    <p>原文例句：The Cyberspace Administration of China, the country’s internet watchdog, for instance, has articulated Beijing’s demand for data security into intrusive requirements that have made it increasingly difficult and costly to comply with. </p>    <p>例句讲解：这个单词来源于Latin，由ad-（向）和articulus（关节）组成，意为“连接，表达”。在这个例句中，它指的是中国网络空间管理局将北京对数据安全的要求明确表述为侵入性要求，使得符合要求变得越来越困难和昂贵。</p></li>  </ul>  <ul>    <li>intrusion (n.) - /ɪntrˈuːʒən/ 入侵，侵入。    <p>原文例句：The Cyberspace Administration of China, the country’s internet watchdog, for instance, has articulated Beijing’s demand for data security into intrusive requirements that have made it increasingly difficult and costly to comply with. </p>    <p>例句讲解：这个单词来源于Latin，由in-（进入）和trudere（推）组成，意为“进入，推入”。在这个例句中，它指的是中国网络空间管理局将北京对数据安全的要求明确表述为侵入性要求，使得符合要求变得越来越困难和昂贵。</p></li>  </ul>  </div><div>  <h2>词组：</h2>  <ul>    <li>in terms of - 就……而言，从……方面来说。    <P>原文例句：Tencent Holdings, the country’s most valuable player that once eyed being Asia’s first US$1 trillion company, fell out of the global top 10 after losing 60 per cent of its market capitalisation, while Post owner Alibaba Group Holding, which exceeded Amazon.com in market value in 2014, is now worth an eighth of the US e-commerce titan. - 腾讯控股作为中国最有价值的企业之一，曾以成为亚洲第一家市值超1万亿美元的公司为目标，但在失去60%的市值后跌出全球前10强，而邮报的所有者阿里巴巴集团控股有限公司，2014年市值超过亚马逊，现在已不及美国这家电子商务巨头的八分之一。</P>    <p>例句讲解：这个词组是由in（在……里面），terms（条件，条款）和of（属于，关于）构成的，表示“按照某种标准或角度来衡量或评价”。在这个例句中，它表示就市值而言，腾讯控股作为中国最有价值的企业之一，曾以成为亚洲第一家市值超1万亿美元的公司为目标，但在失去60%的市值后跌出全球前10强，而邮报的所有者阿里巴巴集团控股有限公司，2014年市值超过亚马逊，现在已不及美国这家电子商务巨头的八分之一。</p></li>  </ul></div><div>  <h2>句子：</h2>  <ul>    <li>China’s disciplinary enforcers add ‘bad’ books, sex, drugs to serious offences - 中国的纪检人员将“不良”书籍、性行为和毒品列为严重犯罪。<p>句子分析：这是一个主谓宾结构的简单句，主语是China’s disciplinary enforcers，谓语是add，宾语是‘bad’ books, sex, drugs。其中add表示添加，to表示至。这个句子的意思是说，中国的纪检人员将“不良”书籍、性行为和毒品列为严重犯罪。</p></li>  </ul></div><div>  <h2>语法：</h2>  <ul>    <li>现在完成时 - 表示从过去某个时间开始一直持续到现在的动作或状态。    <p>原文例句：The South China Morning Post reported on Tuesday that a key gaming official has left his job following the debacle, as the Chinese government tries to allay market fears. </p>    <p>语法讲解：这是一种时态，结构是：have/has + been + 过去分词。其中have/has要根据主语的人称和数进行变化，been是be的过去分词，过去分词是动词的-ed形式。这种时态表示动作或状态从过去某个时间开始一直持续到现在，强调动作或状态的持续性和未完成性。在这个例句中，它表示南华早报周二报道说，一位关键的游戏官员在惨败之后辞去了工作，因为中国政府正试图平息市场恐惧。</p></li>  </ul>   <ul>    <li>虚拟语气 - 表示虚拟、假设或愿望。    <p>原文例句：Beijing’s pursuit of market control, along with China’s economic slowdown and rising geopolitical tensions with the US, have turned Chinese internet stocks into one of the worst-performing assets in the past three years. - 北京对市场控制的追求，加上中国经济放缓以及与美国的地缘政治紧张局势加剧，已使中国互联网股价在过去三年中成为表现最差的资产之一。</P>    <p>语法讲解：这是一种语态，结构是：should/could/would/might/may + 动词原形。其中should表示应该，could表示能够，would表示愿意，might表示可能，may表示允许。这种语态表示对事实的假设、愿望或可能性。在这个例句中，它表示北京对市场控制的追求，加上中国经济放缓以及与美国的地缘政治紧张局势加剧，已使中国互联网股价在过去三年中成为表现最差的资产之一。</p></li>  </ul></div>  <ul><li>The mouthpiece of the Central Party School argued that regulators must stop the practice of swinging between extremes of lax oversight and ‘overly strict’ regulation</li>
<li>The opinion came days after the NPPA wiped out billions of dollars in value from Chinese gaming stocks with draft regulation to restrict spending on video games</li>
</ul><figure><img src="https://cdn.i-scmp.com/sites/default/files/d8/images/canvas/2024/01/03/3319e698-c70a-4b75-a5c4-b17164272de6_6b557a93.jpg" /><figcaption>Tencent’s Game for Peace is seen on a mobile phone in this illustration picture taken May 13, 2019.  Photo: Reuters</figcaption></figure><p>A Chinese Communist Party newspaper has urged the country’s regulators to end their erratic moves against the platform economy, in a sign of growing concern over policy damage to the health of the country’s ailing internet titans.</p><p>A front page opinion piece published by the Study Times, the mouthpiece of the Central Party School, on Wednesday argued that regulators must stop the practice of swinging between extremes of lax oversight and “overly strict” regulation so that China’s Big Tech firms can have room to grow.</p><p>The article, which did not name any specific company or regulator, came days after the National Press and Publication Administration (NPPA) wiped out billions of dollars in value from Chinese gaming stocks with <a href="https://www.scmp.com/tech/big-tech/article/3246011/china-tighten-controls-video-gaming-industry-prompting-sell-tencent-and-neteast-shares" target="_self" title="">proposed regulation to restrict spending on video games.</a> The South China Morning Post reported on Tuesday that <a href="https://www.scmp.com/tech/tech-trends/article/3247044/veteran-chinese-video-gaming-official-steps-down-wake-market-rout-linked-proposed-rule-changes" target="_self" title="">a key gaming official has left his job following the debacle,</a> as the Chinese government tries to allay market fears.</p><h3><a href="https://www.scmp.com/news/china/politics/article/3246511/chinas-disciplinary-enforcers-add-bad-books-sex-drugs-serious-offences" title="">China’s disciplinary enforcers add ‘bad’ books, sex, drugs to serious offences</a></h3><p>The draft proposal is the latest example of regulatory hostility, after Beijing’s campaign of “curbing irrational expansion of capital” in 2020 unleashed a race among different ministries and watchdogs to claim authority in checking and approving internet businesses.</p><p>A long list of Chinese ministries has been sharpening their teeth when it comes to disciplining internet firms. The Cyberspace Administration of China, the country’s internet watchdog, for instance, has articulated Beijing’s demand for data security into intrusive requirements that have made it increasingly difficult and costly to comply with.</p><p>Beijing’s pursuit of market control, along with China’s economic slowdown and rising geopolitical tensions with the US, have turned Chinese internet stocks into one of the worst-performing assets in the past three years. Tencent Holdings, the country’s most valuable player that once eyed being Asia’s first US$1 trillion company, fell out of the global top 10 after losing 60 per cent of its market capitalisation, while Post owner Alibaba Group Holding, which exceeded Amazon.com in market value in 2014, is now worth an eighth of the US e-commerce titan.</p><p>According to the Study Times opinion piece, the erratic regulatory behaviour is “a risk and a challenge” for China as its leading internet firms are left further behind their global peers in terms of competitiveness and growth potential.</p><div class="image-inline-container"><figure><img alt="People play video games in a shopping mall in Beijing, November 18, 2023. Photo: Simon Song" class="image-inline caption" height="1500" src="https://cdn.i-scmp.com/sites/default/files/d8/images/canvas/2024/01/03/643c0e52-aced-4b9f-a2cf-0f56737ce2f0_bd901af2.jpg" title="People play video games in a shopping mall in Beijing, November 18, 2023. Photo: Simon Song" width="2000" /><figcaption>People play video games in a shopping mall in Beijing, November 18, 2023. Photo: Simon Song</figcaption></figure></div><p>China must improve “cross-departmental coordination” to avoid duplicated enforcement and checks, while regulatory acts and policy adjustments must factor in “the views of all parties, especially those being regulated” to avoid interrupting normal business activities or causing unexpected risks, it said.</p><p>Chinese regulators should loosen their grip and allow “self-governance” by Chinese internet companies, it added. “It is important to respect the rationality and necessity of platform self-governance to guide and encourage the formation of self-regulatory mechanisms,” the article said.</p><p>It remains unknown whether China’s different regulators will heed the advice. Beijing’s regulatory crackdown on the internet sector officially came to an end a year ago, when the Chinese leadership said the country’s platform enterprises would be encouraged to “fully display their capabilities” in growth, job creation and international competition.</p> ]]></description>
</item>

